CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: CT angiogram chest with IV contrast (PE protocol) 1/3/2019    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0  Percentile rank: 0 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is <7%.    OTHER FINDINGS: Small sliding type hiatus hernia. Surgical changes from gastric  bypass are partially visualized in the upper abdomen. Mild multilevel lower  thoracic spine degenerative disc disease with osteophyte formation. Mild mosaic  attenuation is seen bilaterally at the bases consistent with mild air trapping.  A 2 mm noncalcified pulmonary nodule is redemonstrated in the right lower lobe  (series 4, image 47) and unchanged from the prior.    IMPRESSION:  The observed coronary calcium score of 0 is at percentile rank 0 %. For  comparison purposes the estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a  group of patients asymptomatic for coronary disease with the same age,  race/ethnicity and gender is less than 7%.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: No prior CT cardiac scoring without IV contrast. PA and lateral  chest radiographs 08/20/2018.    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0  Percentile rank: 0 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 75%.    OTHER FINDINGS:   Fusiform dilatation of the visualized proximal and mid ascending thoracic aorta  measuring up to 22 mm in the visualized midsegment (double oblique measurement,  series 1000).    Partially visualized focal calcification in the left mediastinum correlates with  calcified left hilar lymph nodes on prior chest radiograph and is consistent  with remote granulomatous disease. Nonspecific mildly enlarged noncalcified  subcarinal lymph node, 12 mm, most likely reactive.     Mild peripheral reticular groundglass opacities in the visualized caudal lungs  most conspicuous in the peripheral right middle lobe lateral segment. Fused  bilateral calcified pulmonary micronodules (sub-3 mm) consistent with calcified  pulmonary granulomas/remote granulomatous disease.    Very small esophageal hiatal hernia.    Mild degenerative changes of the skeleton.    IMPRESSION:  1. The observed coronary calcium score of 0 is at percentile rank 0 %.  2. Partially visualized fusiform dilatation of the ascending thoracic aorta, 42  mm.  3. Incidental mild interstitial lung abnormality. Consider dedicated CT chest  interstitial lung disease protocol and/or pulmonary medicine consultation as  clinically warranted particularly if the patient is symptomatic.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH IV CONTRAST, CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV  CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: Outside CT chest with IV contrast 08/02/2018.    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 1  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 7    Agatston score: 8  Percentile rank: 34 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 70%.    CORONARY ARTERIES:    Origins: Conventional.      Dominance: Right.    Left Main Coronary: Widely patent.      Left Anterior Descending:  Small focus of calcified plaque within the proximal  segment immediately upstream to the 1st diagonal results in minimal luminal  narrowing.  Left Circumflex: Widely patent and diminutive distal to the 1st obtuse marginal.    1st Obtuse Marginal: Prominent and widely patent.  Right Coronary: Widely patent.     OTHER CARDIAC FINDINGS:    No first-pass myocardial perfusion defects. Normal LVEF with no regional wall  motion abnormalities. Trileaflet aortic valve with mild leaflet thickening.    ADDITIONAL FINDINGS: Degenerative and hypertrophic changes of the visualized  thoracic spine.  Likely hiatal hernia.    CAD-RADS CATEGORIES: (based on most severe single lesion)    0: 0%, No stenosis     1: 1-24%, Minimal stenosis    2: 25-49%, Mild stenosis    3: 50-69%, Moderate stenosis    4: 70-99%, Severe stenosis    5: 100%, Occluded      Modifiers:  N: Non-diagnostic segment(s)  S: Stent  G: Graft  V: Vulnerable  plaque            IMPRESSION:  1. Small focus of calcified plaque in the proximal LAD resulting in minimal  stenosis.; CAD-RADS1.  2.The observed coronary calcium score of 8 is at percentile rank 34 %.

GUIDELINES FOR FOLLOW-UP of newly detected solid nodules incidentally detected  on CT in persons 35 years or older. (2017 revision)    LOW-RISK PATIENT (Minimal or absent history of smoking or of other known risk  factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then consider CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm  Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then consider CT at 18-24 months      HIGH-RISK PATIENT (History of smoking or of other known risk factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then at 18-24 months    (Nodule size is the average of length and width.)    *Nodules <6mm do not require routine follow-up, but certain patients at high  risk with suspicious nodule morphology, upper lobe location, or both may warrant  12-month follow-up.      Guidelines do not apply to lung cancer screening, patients with  immunosuppression, or patients with a known primary cancer.    IMPRESSION:  1.  The observed coronary calcium score of 0.2 is at percentile rank 68 %.  2.  Left lower lobe pulmonary micronodule for which follow-up considerations  have been provided.

COMPARISON: PA and lateral chest radiographs dating back to 09/18/2018.    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 6  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 6  Percentile rank: 59 % in comparison to a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex.    The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 47%.    OTHER FINDINGS:  Indeterminant 4 mm pure groundglass pulmonary nodule in the peripheral left  lower lobe superior segment (series 4, image 34). Redemonstration of scattered  bilateral subcentimeter pulmonary nodules on topogram, which are unchanged from  PA and lateral chest radiographs 09/19/2018; these should be benign pulmonary  granulomas. Additionally, calcified bilateral hilar lymph nodes are present,  unchanged, and also consistent with remote granulomatous disease. Scattered  colonic diverticula in the splenic flexure without acute diverticulitis. Minimal  degenerative changes of the spine.    RECOMMENDATIONS FOR MANAGEMENT OF SUBSOLID (includes ground glass and  part-solid) PULMONARY NODULES DETECTED AT CT.    SOLITARY PURE GROUND GLASS NODULES (GGNs):  Single nodule size (mm) *:     <6mm No routine CT follow-up required*  6mm or > CT at 6-12 months. If persistent, then CT every 2 years until stable  for 5 years.  FDG PET is not recommended.    PART-SOLID NODULES   Single nodule size (mm) *:     <6mm No routine CT follow-up required*  6mm or >  CT at 3-6 months to confirm persistence#.  If unchanged and solid  component remains <6mm, annual CT should be performed for 5 years.      MULTIPLE GROUND GLASS~ OR PART-SOLID NODULES:  Largest nodule size (mm)*:    <6mm  CT at 3-6 months.  If stable, consider CT at 2 and 4 years.   6mm or >  CT at 3-6 months.  Subsequent management based on the most suspicious  nodule.        *In certain suspicious nodules <6mm, consider follow-up at 2 and 4 years.  If  there is growth or solid component develops, consider resection.    #Persistent part-solid nodules with solid components 6mm or > should be  considered highly suspicious.  ~Multiple <6mm pure ground glass nodules are usually benign, but consider  follow-up at 2 and 4 years in selected patients at high risk.      IMPRESSION:  1. The observed coronary calcium score of 6 is at percentile rank 59 %.           2. Nonspecific 4 mm pure ground glass pulmonary nodule in the superior left  lower lobe that is most likely infectious/inflammatory but indeterminant.  Follow-up guidelines are provided in the findings section of this report.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST  3D/MIPS: 3D Post-Processing performed on a dependent workstation.     COMPARISON: None    TECHNIQUE:  Scanner: 320-detector row CT  ECG gating: Prospectively diastolic  IV contrast: 69 mL Omnipaque 350  Medication(s) administered: 0.4 mg SL nitroglycerin    FINDINGS:  Quality: Fair.  Coronary artery calcium score: Total Agatston score 109.38 (all in the LAD). The  score is consistent with moderate calcified plaque burden, and is at 74th  percentile for matched age, race, and gender.  Coronary dominance: Right.    Left main coronary artery (LM)  Anomaly: None.  Plaque: None.  Stenosis: None.    Left anterior descending coronary artery (LAD)  Anomaly: None.  Plaque: Densely calcified plaque localized in the short mid segment of the LAD  and diffuse non-calcified plaques in the entire LAD.  Stenosis: Indeterminate stenosis in the mid LAD due to densely calcified plaque  (suspected to be moderate or 50-69% stenosis). The long, small distal segment  has tandem moderate (50-69%) and severe (>/=70%) stenoses from non-calcified  plaques.  Diagonal branch (D): D1 is a small artery with severe ostial and proximal  stenoses from non-calcified plaques. D2 is a relatively bigger artery with mild  ostial stenosis (25-49%) from calcified plaque.    Left circumflex coronary artery (LCx)  Anomaly: None.  Plaque: Small focal calcified plaque in the distal segment.  Stenosis: Minimal to none (<25%).  Obtuse marginal branch: Tiny.    Right coronary artery (RCA)  Anomaly: None.  Plaque: Mild, non-calcified.  Stenosis: Minimal (<25%).  Right posterior descending artery (RPDA): No significant stenosis proximally.  Moderate luminal irregularities more distally.  Right posterolateral branches (RPLA): Small with no significant stenosis  proximally.  Acute marginal branch: Mild proximal stenosis (25-49%) from non-calcified  plaque.    Cardiac and extracardiac findings:  Normal 4 chambers. No intracardiac mass/thrombus identified. No interatrial and  interventricular septal defect. Normal pulmonary veins. Normal pulmonary  arteries. Tiny focal calcification at the sinotubular junction. Normal thoracic  aorta diameter with no atherosclerosis within the field of view (distal and  transverse aorta not in field of view). No pericardial effusion.      IMPRESSION:  1. Total coronary calcium score 109.38 Agatston units.  2. Indeterminate stenosis (suspected to be moderate) from densely calcified  plaque in the mid LAD.  3. Tandem moderate (50-69%) and severe (>/=70%) stenoses from non-calcified  plaques in the small distal LAD.  4. Severe ostial and proximal stenoses from non-calcified plaques in small D1.      IMPRESSION INCIDENTAL FINDINGS: Small esophageal hiatal hernia. Upper abdomen  otherwise negative. No significant mediastinal or hilar adenopathy. Visualized  lungs are negative. Osseous structures are negative. Please see cardiologist  report for coronary artery findings.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM TRIPLE RULE OUT WITH IV CONTRAST, CT CARDIAC SCORING  WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ECG-gated CT angiogram of the chest with IV contrast done according to the acute  chest pain protocol, including independent workstation 3D reformations.        COMPARISON:  No prior cross-sectional imaging of the chest is available at this  time. PA and lateral chest radiographs 01/23/2019.    FINDINGS:    PULMONARY ARTERIES:  Negative for acute pulmonary embolism. Nondilated main pulmonary arteries.    THORACIC AORTA:   Nonaneurysmal. Negative for intramural hematoma, dissection, or penetrating  atherosclerotic ulcer. Minimal atherosclerotic plaque of the aortic arch and  descending thoracic aorta. Left-sided aortic arch with normal variant direct  origin of the left vertebral artery.    CORONARY CALCIUM CT:  Noncontrast CT scan of the heart was done for coronary artery calcification  scoring.  The examination is positive and shows definite calcium deposits which  are diagnostic of atherosclerotic disease.        The calcium score is 3278. This amount of calcifications is greater than  expected and places the patient at the 99th percentile for amount of  calcification when compared to an age and gender-matched peer group. Calcium is  present in the left main, left anterior descending, left circumflex, and right  coronary arteries.    CORONARY CTA:  Image quality: Degraded by diffuse coronary artery calcification and cardiac  pulsation artifact despite maximum intravenous Lopressor administration per  radiology protocol. Heart rate average is 78.  Origins/course: Normal.  Dominance: Right.  Left Main Coronary: Patent. Predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque in  the distal segment immediately proximal to the bifurcation results in less than  50% luminal stenosis.  Left Anterior Descending: Patent. Diffuse predominantly calcified  atherosclerotic plaque in all segments beginning at the origin. Calcification  significantly degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis.  Left Circumflex: Patent. Diffuse predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque  in all segments significantly degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis. Distal  segment terminates as a dominant second obtuse marginal branch.  Right Coronary: Patent. No luminal stenosis of the origin.  Otherwise, diffuse  predominantly calcified atherosclerotic plaque in all segments significantly  degrades evaluation for luminal stenosis.    OTHER CARDIOVASCULAR FINDINGS:  No resting left ventricular myocardial perfusion defect. Normal biventricular  myocardial thickness, chamber size, and systolic function by qualitative  assessment. Evaluation of the right atrium is degraded by mixing of opacified  blood from the SVC and unopacified blood from the IVC.    Mild thickening and minimal calcification of the aortic valve cusps.    ADDITIONAL FINDINGS:   Bilateral anterior posterior cervical, subpectoral, axillary, mediastinal, and  hilar lymphadenopathy. Lymphadenopathy is greatest in the axillary and  subpectoral chains. Examples: Right subpectoral lymph node, 66 mm x 28 mm  (series 5, image 27). Subcarinal lymph node, 34 mm x 20 mm (series 5, image  124). Right hilar lymph node 38 mm x 23 mm (series 5, image 104).    Mild residual thymus/thymic hyperplasia.    Trace simple inferior pericardial effusion.     Trace simple layering bilateral pleural effusions.    Diffuse bronchial wall thickening. Nodular noncavitary peribronchovascular  consolidation and adjacent groundglass opacities in all segments of the right  upper lobe greatest in the posterior segment. Multifocal and bilateral upper  lobe and centrilobular and tree-in-bud distribution predominant solid and  groundglass micronodularity also greatest in the right upper lobe.    Cortical and intramedullary osseous sclerotic lesion without soft tissue mass or  pathologic fracture in the left glenoid (series 5, image 11). Mild symmetric  gynecomastia. Mild dependent subcutaneous body wall edema.    CAD-RADS CATEGORIES: (based on most severe single lesion)  0: 0%, No stenosis   1: 1-24%, Minimal stenosis  2: 25-49%, Mild stenosis  3: 50-69%, Moderate stenosis  4: 70-99%, Severe stenosis  5: 100%, Occluded    Modifiers:  N: Non-diagnostic segment(s)  S: Stent  G: Graft  V: Vulnerable plaque      IMPRESSION:    1. Left main and three vessel predominantly calcified coronary artery disease.  Coronary calcium score is 3278. CAD RADS N. Alternative cardiac testing should  be considered.  2. Negative for thoracic aortic aneurysm, intramural hematoma, dissection, and  penetrating atherosclerotic ulcer. Minimal thoracic aortic calcified  atherosclerotic plaque.  3. Negative for acute pulmonary embolism.  4. Nonspecific nodular noncavitary pulmonary consolidation in the right upper  lobe and multifocal and bilateral pulmonary micronodularity greatest in the  right upper lobe. Consider atypical infection and drug toxicity.  5. Trace bilateral pleural and pericardial simple effusions.  6. Bulky inferior cervical and thoracic lymphadenopathy consistent with clinical  history of CLL.  7. Indeterminate osseous sclerotic lesion in the left glenoid. No associated  soft tissue mass or pathologic fracture.

For  example in the right lower lobe (series 2, image 52), left lower lobe (series 2,  image 57), and left upper lobe (series 2, image 19).     GUIDELINES FOR FOLLOW-UP of newly detected solid nodules incidentally detected  on CT in persons 35 years or older. (2017 revision)    LOW-RISK PATIENT (Minimal or absent history of smoking or of other known risk  factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then consider CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm  Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months    HIGH-RISK PATIENT (History of smoking or of other known risk factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with  CT at 3 months Guidelines do not apply to lung cancer screening, patients with  immunosuppression, or patients with a known primary cancer. Recommend comparing those exams.

COMPARISON: None    TECHNIQUE AND QUALITY:  Acquisition mode: Prospective ECG triggering  Contrast type and volume: Iohexol 350 mg iodine/mL 70 mL  Medication used: Nitroglycerin 800 mcg SL, Metoprolol 5mg IV  Complications: None  Image quality: Good signal noise. No significant artifacts.   Scanner: Aquilion ONE ViSION    FINDINGS:  Coronary Calcium (Agatston unit):   LM: 0  RCA: 59.3  LAD: 300  LCX: 18.4  TOTAL: 378  Percentile age/gender cohort: 82 percentile for age, gender, and  race/ethnicity-matched group per MESA database.    Cardiovascular Angiography:  Large ascending aortic pseudoaneurysm with organizing thrombus measured at  maximum 7.8 cm in diameter.  Proximal intimal tear/dissection is  posterior-superiorly adjacent to the left main ostium.  Maximum diameter of the  tear is measured at 4.9 mm.  A more distal intimal tear/dissection is localized  in the right posterior wall of the mid ascending aorta and measured at maximum 7  mm in diameter.  The pseudoaneurysm compresses on the right pulmonary artery,  causing severe slit-like narrowing.  In addition, there is a fistula  communicating between the pseudoaneurysm and the right pulmonary artery with  maximum diameter measured at 5.6 mm.    Bileaflet mechanical prosthesis in aortic valve position. Both leaflets in  closing position.  No thrombus identified on or near the leaflets.  Small (<5  mm) hypo-enhancing density is seen below the left-anterior segment of the lower  sewing ring in the LVOT.  Small, hemodynamically insignificant thrombus is  suspected.  Dual-chamber pacemaker leads identified in right atrium and right  ventricle.  The tip of the RV lead is localized in the RV apex.  The tip of the  RA lead is on the interatrial septum.  No evidence of left to right interatrial  shunt.    No evidence of thrombus in the left atrium and left atrial appendage.  Normally  connected right and left pulmonary veins.  Right pulmonary venous return appears  less opacified than left pulmonary venous return.  Normally connected coronary  sinus, superior and inferior vena cava.  No pericardial effusion.    Coronary Angiography:  1) Left main:  Widely patent.  2) Left anterior descending (LAD):  Multifocal calcified and noncalcified  plaques in the proximal and mid segments.  Mild nonobstructive atherosclerosis  in the proximal segment (25-49% stenosis).  Intermediate atherosclerosis in the  mid segment (45-55% stenosis).  Due to indeterminate atherosclerotic disease in  the mid segment, study is submitted for CT FFR analysis.  3) Right coronary artery (RCA):  The ostium of the right coronary artery is  widely patent.  The rest of the right coronary artery has minimal nonobstructive  atherosclerosis (25% stenosis or less).  4) Left circumflex (LCX):  Codominant.  Minimal nonobstructive atherosclerosis  (<25% stenosis).   5) Ramus intermedius:  Tiny and not well-visualized.    Non-Cardiac Findings: No significant airspace disease in visualized lung field.  There is a large periaortic fluid collection along the root of the aorta  measuring 7.6 cm which is unchanged. There is continued enhancement of a large  pseudoaneurysm along the posterior aspect of this perinephric fluid collection  measures approximately 5.2 cm in size. Coronary artery findings. Dictated by the  cardiology service. Moderate cardiomegaly. Moderate mass effect on the right  pulmonary artery. Mild left lower lobe atelectasis.    IMPRESSION:  1.  Total coronary calcium score measured at 378 Agatston units or 82 percentile  for age, gender, and race/ethnicity-matched group per MESA database.  2.  Intermediate (45-55% stenosis) atherosclerotic coronary artery disease in  the mid LAD segment.  CT FFR analysis is pending.  3.  Ascending aortic pseudoaneurysm with a proximal tear/dissection adjacent to  left main ostium, a distal dissection in the mid segment of ascending aorta (in  field of view), a communicating fistula to the right pulmonary artery, and  severe slit-like narrowing of the right pulmonary artery due to compression by  the pseudoaneurysm.  4.  Small (<5 mm) thrombus below the left-anterior segment of the lower sewing  ring in the LVOT is suspected.  5.  The tip of the RA pacemaker lead is on the interatrial septum.  Recommend  correlating with prior imaging.  6.  Please refer to non-cardiac findings by radiology service.

Recommend  correlating with prior imaging.  6.  Please refer to non-cardiac findings by radiology service.

CT_report: Indications: Nonrheumatic aortic (valve) stenosis;CAD and bicuspid AV   ORIGINAL REPORT - 29-Aug-2018 23:51:00   CT Angio Coronary         IMPRESSION: At least moderate three-vessel coronary disease which appears severe in the distal left circumflex distribution as described below. Further characterization with catheterization is recommended, provided that it is clinically warranted.  The degree of stenosis is difficult to accurately predict with this examination due to a combination of blooming artifact from extensive calcified plaque and motion artifact related to a relatively rapid heart rate.      Coronary calcium score: 1092, This is a very high calcium score generally associated with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related death) of up to 10.8 times patients with 0 calcium scores.      Typed 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with mild aortic stenosis by planimetry, opening area of the aortic valve approximately 2.2 sq cm. No associated aortic disease, no aneurysm or coarctation. Thoracic aorta appears normal.         CLINICAL HISTORY: Aortic valve disease, bicuspid valve, evaluate aorta, also evaluate coronary arteries.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.  Images were postprocessed on an independent 3-D workstation in order to calculate the patient's calcium score.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a retrospectively R-wave triggered helical cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at multiple phases of the R-R interval.  Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an independent 3-D workstation.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.         COMPARE: No prior studies are available for comparison.         VASCULAR FINDINGS: Right dominant coronary circulation.      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 1092. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 435 , left circumflex 283, and right coronary artery 374.      Left main coronary artery: Normal sized artery, free of significant atherosclerotic disease, no significant stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Several large calcified plaque scattered throughout the left anterior descending coronary artery. There is circumferential calcified plaque at the origin of the LAD appears to cause moderate, between 50 and 70%, loss of luminal diameter. Large calcified plaque in the distal LAD associated with positive remodeling also appears to cause moderate, between 50% and 70%, loss of diameter. LAD gives off several small diagonal and circumflex perforator branches.      Right coronary artery: A large vessel, within the distal aspect of the proximal and proximal aspect of the mid right coronary artery there is extensive calcified plaque and positive remodeling. Evaluation of this vessel is degraded by motion artifact related to the patient's relatively rapid heart rate, suspect that there is at least moderate (50-70% loss of diameter) disease in this region.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal-sized vessel. Some eccentric calcified plaque at the origin of the left circumflex appears to cause mild, slightly less than 50%, loss of luminal diameter. Within the distal left circumflex there is a long, irregular, calcified plaque extending over 2.3 cm in vessel associated with some positive remodeling. There appears to be at least moderate and probably severe, greater than 70%, loss of diameter.      There is a type 1 L-R bicuspid aortic valve with thickened and calcified raphe between the right and left sinuses of Valsalva. The leaflets are moderately to severely thickened with a moderate to severe amount of associated calcification which does not appear to extend into the annulus. By planimetry, the opening area of the bowel is approximately 2.2 sq cm. The annulus is 28 x 23 mm, sinuses of Valsalva measuring 38 x 34 mm, sinotubular junction measures 30 x 29 mm, tubular ascending aorta measures up to 35 x 34 mm.      Left ventricle appears normal in size and systolic function, estimated ejection fraction is greater than 70%. No focal wall motion abnormalities are seen. End-diastolic volume approximately 190 mL, end-systolic volume approximately 50 mL, stroke volume approximately 140 mL. There is borderline concentric left ventricular hypertrophy, left ventricular wall measures up to 12 mm in thickness. There is mild mitral valve prolapse in the left atrium is enlarged. Qualitatively, right ventricular size and systolic function appear normal.      Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. No aneurysm or coarctation. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.         NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Mild upper lobe predominant centrilobular and paraseptal emphysematous changes. Some calcified nodules in the right lower lobe are consistent with old granulomatous disease. No significant edema, effusion, or pneumothorax, no pneumonia.      No significant pericardial effusion is seen. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Calcified right hilar lymph nodes are consistent with old granulomatous disease.  Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates stigmata of cirrhosis and portal hypertension with TIPS, splenomegaly, varices, postembolization changes left upper quadrant. No acute appearing fractures or dislocations.                  Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 29-Aug-2018 23:51

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None    TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification  scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial  reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation  in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       ADDITIONAL FINDINGS: Benign-appearing 4 mm nodule along the minor fissure,  series 3 image 20. 5 mm benign-appearing nodule along the minor fissure series 3  image 33. 6 mm solid, noncalcified and well circumscribed lingular pulmonary  nodule anterior to left hilum, series 3 image 17. 4 mm nodule along the left  major fissure within the lingula, series 3 image 31. Mild bibasilar atelectasis.  Visualized portions of the lungs are otherwise clear.        Several borderline enlarged mediastinal and hilar lymph nodes which, given the  pulmonary nodules, likely reflect the sequela of old granulomatous disease. One  of the larger lymph nodes, a low right paratracheal lymph node measures  approximately 21 x 10 mm, series 3 image 8. Some mild dilatation of the aortic  root at the level of the sinuses of Valsalva measures approximately 39 mm in  diameter. Heart appears normal in size, no pericardial effusion. Limited  evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates some cholelithiasis and a small  gastrohepatic lymph node, series 3 image 58 as well as a few scattered  pericardial lymph nodes series 3 image 54, series 3 image 59 not significantly  enlarged. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen.    IMPRESSION:  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 30% of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    A few scattered solid, benign-appearing but indeterminate pulmonary nodules  measuring up to 6 mm. There is also some mildly prominent lymphadenopathy in the  mediastinum. Probably related to old granulomatous disease. In lieu of any  outside imaging for comparison, recommend a follow-up chest CT in 12 months to  reevaluate/document stability.

COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       ADDITIONAL FINDINGS: Benign-appearing 4 mm nodule along the minor fissure,  series 3 image 20. 5 mm benign-appearing nodule along the minor fissure series 3  image 33. 6 mm solid, noncalcified and well circumscribed lingular pulmonary  nodule anterior to left hilum, series 3 image 17. 4 mm nodule along the left  major fissure within the lingula, series 3 image 31. Mild bibasilar atelectasis.  Visualized portions of the lungs are otherwise clear.        Several borderline enlarged mediastinal and hilar lymph nodes which, given the  pulmonary nodules, likely reflect the sequela of old granulomatous disease. One  of the larger lymph nodes, a low right paratracheal lymph node measures  approximately 21 x 10 mm, series 3 image 8. Some mild dilatation of the aortic  root at the level of the sinuses of Valsalva measures approximately 39 mm in  diameter. Heart appears normal in size, no pericardial effusion. Limited  evaluation of the upper abdomen demonstrates some cholelithiasis and a small  gastrohepatic lymph node, series 3 image 58 as well as a few scattered  pericardial lymph nodes series 3 image 54, series 3 image 59 not significantly  enlarged. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen.    IMPRESSION:  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 30% of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    A few scattered solid, benign-appearing but indeterminate pulmonary nodules  measuring up to 6 mm. There is also some mildly prominent lymphadenopathy in the  mediastinum. Probably related to old granulomatous disease. In lieu of any  outside imaging for comparison, recommend a follow-up chest CT in 12 months to  reevaluate/document stability.

CT_report: EXAM:  CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH IV CONTRAST  Including 3D image post-processing.       CLINICAL INFORMATION:  Chest pain, anginal equivalent.        COMPARISON: None available.    TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed prior to the administration of  intravenous contrast using prospective ECG gating and reconstruction of  contiguous axial images through the heart during diastole. Postprocessing was  performed on an independent 3D workstation in order to calculate the patient's  calcium score according to the Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.  Subsequently, Intravenous contrast was administered and a CT of the heart was  done with prospective ECG gating during a single breath-held aquisition. A  diastolic-phase axial thin slice (>1mm) reconstruction was performed and sent to  an independant workstation for further processing. Iodinated contrast was  administered intravenously; see the patient's electronic medical record for the  amount and type of contrast administered and wasted. Premedication with  Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol. 3-D  reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating  oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an  independent 3-D workstation.      CORONARY FINDINGS: The patient has normal coronary anatomy. Coronary circulation  is Right dominant.    Calcium Score: Left main = zero; Left anterior descending = zero; Circumflex =  zero; Right =zero  Total score: zero    Left main coronary artery: Normal, no disease; no stenosis.    Left anterior descending coronary artery system: Normal with normal diagonal  branches, no disease; no stenosis. Motion and streak artifacts along the  proximal circumflex.    Left circumflex coronary artery: Normal with normal obtuse marginal branches, no  disease; no stenosis. Right coronary artery: Mild motion artifacts of the right  coronary just distal to the origin of the acute marginal. Otherwise, Normal with  normal posterior descending branch, no disease; no stenosis.    Artifacts noted along the proximal circumflex, as well as the right coronary  just distal to the origin of the marginal appear less prominent on the  reconstructed images at the 43% of the R-R interval without discrete significant  stenosis..      OTHER FINDINGS: The lungs are clear. No pleural effusion, no pneumothorax. No  thoracic lymphadenopathy. Visualized portions of the upper abdomen are  unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen..      IMPRESSION:  Total calcium score: 0 A zero coronary calcium score in an  asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative predictive value for  hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac related death), exceeding  95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    Coronary CT angiography shows no significant stenosis. CT_report: Indications: ST Elevation   ORIGINAL REPORT - 19-Sep-2011 16:45:00   CT Angio Coronary:      IMPRESSION:   #1. Very large pericardial effusion with compression of the atria.   #2. Significant coronary artery disease. The left-sided disease may be chronic given the small size of the vessels and visible collaterals from the right side. The large right coronary artery contains a stenosis of significance approximately 60-70% in its proximal portion. The LAD, ramus intermedius, and left circumflex divisions all contain significant stenoses and/or occlusions as discussed.   #3. Type B dissection.      Technique: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous 2.5 mm axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval. Subsequently, intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 70% of the R-R interval. The source 0.625 axial images were transferred to the Advantage Windows workstation for real-time multiplanar reformatting. Short and long axis views and rotating oblique reformatted views were also performed of the coronary arteries.      Premedication with Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.      Contrast: 120 mL Visipaque. 30 mL discarded.      FINDINGS: The coronary calcium scores 911. This places the patient in the 94th percentile based on comparison to age and sex matched controls.      Following intravenous contrast there is excellent opacification of a right dominant system. Post sternotomy with aortic valve replacement and reimplantation of the coronary arteries. There is a very large pericardial effusion particularly overlying the right atrium, where it measures 4 cm in width and is associated with some compression of the atrial chambers. Fluid is also present superiorly and at the cardiac base overlying the left ventricle. There is a small left pleural effusion 2 cm in AP diameter with adjacent atelectasis. The dissection in the descending aorta is still visible with true and false lumena of similar size. The overall size of the aorta is approximately 3.9 cm. The true lumen measures 2 cm in diameter.      Air is present within the pericardium consistent with the recent nature of the surgery.      The left main coronary artery appears patent. The left anterior descending artery contains abundant calcification limiting assessment. Proximally this calcification is very dense and there is a small noncalcified plaque axial image 124 that causes a very high-grade stenosis. Distally, calcified and noncalcified plaque is also associated with areas where the lumen is nearly completely occluded. The first diagonal is quite small and the second diagonal contains a significant stenosis shortly after its origin. Distally the LAD is poorly visualized and probably occluded. This may be chronic. There are significant collaterals arising from the right-sided circulation. The right coronary artery is patent at its origin and the conus branch and marginal branches are prominent. There is a focal noncalcified plaque image 183 causing approximately 60-70% stenosis immediately proximal to the first marginal branch. This is a short segment stenosis and distally the right coronary artery is patent and gives rise to a posterior ventricular branch and to the posterior descending artery. The right coronary artery is a large vessel.      The left circumflex coronary artery is quite diminutive. It terminates as very small marginal branches that are difficult to assess due to their small size. There is also ramus branch that contains a significant stenosis shortly after its origin.      The cardiac chambers are otherwise grossly unremarkable in size. Pulmonary arteries unremarkable.      IMPRESSION:   #1. Very large pericardial effusion with compression of the atria.   #2. Significant coronary artery disease. The left-sided disease may be chronic given the small size of the vessels and visible collaterals from the right side. The large right coronary artery contains a stenosis of significance approximately 60-70% in its proximal portion. The LAD, ramus intermedius, and left circumflex divisions all contain significant stenoses and/or occlusions as discussed.   #3. Type B dissection.       This report has been electronically signed by Gruden, James MD on Sep 19 2011  4:45PM.         Electronically signed by:    J.F. Gruden M.D. 19-Sep-2011 16:45

CT_report: 18-Feb-2011 08:39:00  Exam: CTA Coronary with calc scoring   Indications: cta th/abd aorta- aortic valve stenosis acquired; fatigue; SOB;PARTNER Trial/CTA Abd and Pelvis With 3D - Perform at MAYO E3 OR SMH 6 JOSEPH**CT w/dye "no cath within 24 hours"   ORIGINAL REPORT - 18-Feb-2011 11:44:00   EXAM: ECG gated CT angiogram of the chest and heart, including independent workstation review and 3-D reformations, performed as part of a PARTNER protocol.       CONCLUSION/IMPRESSION:    1. Calcific aortic stenosis with an AV calcium score of 3881.   2. Severe 3-vessel coronary artery disease with long segment occlusion of the right coronary artery and significant stenoses of the mid left anterior descending and mid left circumflex arteries. Right dominant system.   3. Mild dilatation of the mid ascending aorta to 40mm in diameter.      FINDINGS: There is extensive calcification of the aortic valve involving mainly the right and noncoronary cusps. The aortic valve calcium score is 3881. The coronary calcium score was 615 which places patient at the 96th percentile for amount of calcium compared to age and sex matched peer group.      The distance from the aortic annulus to the left main coronary artery origin is 16 mm. Aortic annulus diameter is 29 mm. The sinuses of Valsalva diameter is 37 mm. The sinotubular junction diameter is 27 mm. There is dilatation of the ascending aorta to a maximum of 40 mm at the level of the pulmonary artery bifurcation. The remainder of the thoracic aorta is normal caliber with minimal atheromatous changes. Please see 3D lab reconstructions for additional aortic diameter measurements.      There is severe 3-vessel coronary artery disease with mixed calcified and noncalcified plaquescausing complete occlusion of the proximal and mid right coronary artery and significant stenoses of the mid left anterior descending artery and mid left circumflex artery. Right dominant system. Concentric left ventricular hypertrophy. Hypokinesis at the base inferior wall. Tree in bud type infiltrate in the right lower lobe with multiple associated calcified granulomas is possibly all chronic and due to prior infection. Calcified right hilar nodes. FINDINGS:   CORONARY CALCIUM SCORE: CT scan of the heart was done to evaluate for coronary artery calcifications. The scan is negative for calcium deposits in the coronary arteries. Left circumflex:  Widely patent and negative for stenosis, including obtuse marginal branches.   Right coronary artery:  Widely patent and negative for stenosis, including posterolateral and posterior descending branches.      Pericardium: Small pericardial effusion, which may represent generous physiologic fluid. No  appreciable underlying pericardial thickening.      Additional Findings: Separate drainage of the right middle lobe pulmonary vein, normal variant. Tiny calcified granuloma right lower lobe.         Electronically signed by:    C. CT_report: EXAM:  CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST  Including 3D image post-processing.    COMPARISON:  None        CARDIOVASCULAR FINDINGS:        CORONARY ARTERIES:  Coronary calcium score: 1706 (90th percentile).  Dominance: Right coronary artery dominance.  Left Main Coronary: Widely patent and negative for stenosis.  Left Anterior Descending: Dense calcifications in the proximal LAD with no more  than mild (<50%) associated stenosis. Moderate (50-69%) stenosis of the distal  LAD, which is patent nearly to the cardiac apex. Moderate (50-69%) stenosis of a  prominent 1st diagonal branch.  Left Circumflex: Dense calcifications in the mid LCx, which could mask a  moderate stenosis. Small, patent 1st and 2nd obtuse marginal branches.  Right Coronary Artery: Dense calcifications in the proximal RCA. Moderate  luminal stenosis of the proximal/mid RCA. The distal RCA, including posterior  descending and small posterolateral branches, remain patent.     OTHER CARDIAC FINDINGS:    Borderline prominence of the left and right atria. Grossly normal caliber left  and right ventricles. Cine images demonstrate no obvious regional wall motion  abnormalities, although these images are somewhat limited by noise artifact.    ADDITIONAL FINDINGS:      Mild bronchial wall thickening in both lower lungs. Bilateral pleural thickening  and calcification. Bandlike atelectasis in the right lung base may represent  developing round atelectasis. Comparison with any prior outside chest CTs could  be helpful to ensure stability. Hypertrophic changes in the thoracic spine.    CAD-RADS CATEGORIES: (based on most severe single lesion)    0: 0%, No stenosis     1: 1-24%, Minimal stenosis    2: 25-49%, Mild stenosis    3: 50-69%, Moderate stenosis    4: 70-99%, Severe stenosis    5: 100%, Occluded      Modifiers:  N: Non-diagnostic segment(s)  S: Stent  G: Graft  V: Vulnerable  plaque            IMPRESSION:  1. Extensive three-vessel coronary artery calcifications; coronary calcium score  = 1706 (90th percentile).  2. Technical factors, including dense calcification, limit luminal evaluation of  the coronary arteries; CAD-RADS = 3/N.

Chest_Xray_report: 05/21/2009    PA AND LATERAL UPRIGHT CHEST    CLINICAL HISTORY:  Postbypass.    FINDINGS:  Prior study dated 04/21/2009 is available for comparison.     Postsurgical changes in the mediastinum are present.  Dual lead ICD    device remains in place with leads unchanged in position.  Several    abandoned leads are identified overlying the left hemithorax. Right    PICC line catheter has been removed.  There is no evidence for    pneumothorax.  There is poor definition of the left heart border    which is prominent.  Right basilar scar persists unchanged.  No acute    infiltrate is seen.      IMPRESSION:  Stable postoperative chest.
CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery  calcification scoring protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent  3D workstation as ordered by the treating provider and reviewed by the  radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 405  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 1770  Circumflex coronary artery: 42  Right coronary artery: 2744    Agatston score: 5401  Percentile: Greater than 75th    OTHER FINDINGS: Sternotomy and CABG. Mild interstitial prominence in the lingula  and lower lung field suggests fibrotic change, without honeycombing. Retained  epicardial pacer wires. Prominent heart size.     IMPRESSION:  1. The aortic valve calcium score measures 3433.90    2. Coronary calcium score is 5401.    This represents Greater than 75th in comparison to a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex.                        The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients  asymptomatic for coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and  sex is 92%.    3. Incidental findings: Sternotomy and CABG. Mild interstitial prominence in the  lingula and lower lung field suggests fibrotic change and atelectasis, without  honeycombing. Retained epicardial pacer wires. Prominent heart size.

CT_report: 17-Jan-2017 07:24:00  Exam: CT CORONARY wo Lmtd.   Indications: Fam Hx Coronary Artery Disease (CAD)   ORIGINAL REPORT - 17-Jan-2017 09:19:00   EXAM:  CT CORONARY wo Lmtd.      COMPARISON:  01/16/2017 chest x-ray      IMPRESSION:   1. Coronary calcium score of 5.3 (58th percentile of age and gender matched peer group).   2. Circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophagus and borderline prominent periesophageal lymph nodes. Inflammatory or neoplastic processes are diagnostic considerations. Recommend clinical correlation and consider endoscopic evaluation.   3. Tiny indeterminant noncalcified pulmonary lymph nodes measuring less than 4 mm.      FINDINGS      CARDIOVASCULAR:   CT scan of the heart was done to evaluate for coronary artery calcifications. The examination is positive and shows definite calcium deposits which are diagnostic of atherosclerotic disease.      The calcium score is 5.3. This amount of calcifications is greater than expected and places the patient at the 58th percentile for amount of calcification when compared to an age and gender-matched peer group. Calcium is present in the left anterior descending and right coronary arteries.      Atheromatous calcifications of the descending thoracic aorta.         NONVASCULAR:   Few scattered tiny noncalcified indeterminate pulmonary nodules measuring up to 3 mm in the right lower lobe adjacent to the diaphragm (2/57), posterolateral right lower lobe (2/23 and 2/59), anterolateral right middle lobe (2/35). Probable intrapulmonary lymph node adjacent to the right minor fissure (2/17).      Tiny esophageal hiatal hernia. Circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophagus with regional borderline prominent periesophageal lymph nodes (to/51-72) may represent an inflammatory process, however, a neoplastic process also remains a consideration. Recommend clinical correlation and consideration of endoscopy. Postoperative changes lower cervical spine.         GUIDELINES FOR FOLLOW-UP of solid nodules detected incidentally at CT (newly-detected indeterminate nodule in persons 35 years of age or older).~ These apply to solitary pulmonary nodules or multiple pulmonary nodules. If multiple nodules are present, then the size of the largest nodule determines follow-up. No significant artifacts.   Scanner: Aquilion ONE ViSION    FINDINGS:  Coronary Calcium (Agatston unit):   LM: 0  RCA: 59.3  LAD: 300  LCX: 18.4  TOTAL: 378  Percentile age/gender cohort: 82 percentile for age, gender, and  race/ethnicity-matched group per MESA database.    Cardiovascular Angiography:  Large ascending aortic pseudoaneurysm with organizing thrombus measured at  maximum 7.8 cm in diameter.  Proximal intimal tear/dissection is  posterior-superiorly adjacent to the left main ostium.  Maximum diameter of the  tear is measured at 4.9 mm.  A more distal intimal tear/dissection is localized  in the right posterior wall of the mid ascending aorta and measured at maximum 7  mm in diameter.  The pseudoaneurysm compresses on the right pulmonary artery,  causing severe slit-like narrowing.  In addition, there is a fistula  communicating between the pseudoaneurysm and the right pulmonary artery with  maximum diameter measured at 5.6 mm.    Bileaflet mechanical prosthesis in aortic valve position. Both leaflets in  closing position.  No thrombus identified on or near the leaflets.  Small (<5  mm) hypo-enhancing density is seen below the left-anterior segment of the lower  sewing ring in the LVOT.  Small, hemodynamically insignificant thrombus is  suspected.  Dual-chamber pacemaker leads identified in right atrium and right  ventricle.  The tip of the RV lead is localized in the RV apex.  The tip of the  RA lead is on the interatrial septum.  No evidence of left to right interatrial  shunt.    No evidence of thrombus in the left atrium and left atrial appendage.  Normally  connected right and left pulmonary veins.  Right pulmonary venous return appears  less opacified than left pulmonary venous return.  Normally connected coronary  sinus, superior and inferior vena cava.  No pericardial effusion.    Coronary Angiography:  1) Left main:  Widely patent.  2) Left anterior descending (LAD):  Multifocal calcified and noncalcified  plaques in the proximal and mid segments.  Mild nonobstructive atherosclerosis  in the proximal segment (25-49% stenosis).  Intermediate atherosclerosis in the  mid segment (45-55% stenosis).  Due to indeterminate atherosclerotic disease in  the mid segment, study is submitted for CT FFR analysis.  3) Right coronary artery (RCA):  The ostium of the right coronary artery is  widely patent.  The rest of the right coronary artery has minimal nonobstructive  atherosclerosis (25% stenosis or less).  4) Left circumflex (LCX):  Codominant.  Minimal nonobstructive atherosclerosis  (<25% stenosis).   5) Ramus intermedius:  Tiny and not well-visualized.    Non-Cardiac Findings: No significant airspace disease in visualized lung field.  There is a large periaortic fluid collection along the root of the aorta  measuring 7.6 cm which is unchanged. There is continued enhancement of a large  pseudoaneurysm along the posterior aspect of this perinephric fluid collection  measures approximately 5.2 cm in size. Coronary artery findings. Dictated by the  cardiology service. Moderate cardiomegaly. Moderate mass effect on the right  pulmonary artery. Mild left lower lobe atelectasis.    IMPRESSION:  1.  Total coronary calcium score measured at 378 Agatston units or 82 percentile  for age, gender, and race/ethnicity-matched group per MESA database.  2.  Intermediate (45-55% stenosis) atherosclerotic coronary artery disease in  the mid LAD segment.  CT FFR analysis is pending.  3.  Ascending aortic pseudoaneurysm with a proximal tear/dissection adjacent to  left main ostium, a distal dissection in the mid segment of ascending aorta (in  field of view), a communicating fistula to the right pulmonary artery, and  severe slit-like narrowing of the right pulmonary artery due to compression by  the pseudoaneurysm.  4.  Small (<5 mm) thrombus below the left-anterior segment of the lower sewing  ring in the LVOT is suspected.  5.  The tip of the RA pacemaker lead is on the interatrial septum.  Recommend  correlating with prior imaging.  6.  Please refer to non-cardiac findings by radiology service.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    TECHNIQUE: ECG-gated CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification scoring  protocol. Post-processing was performed on an independent 3D workstation as ordered by the treating  provider and reviewed by the radiologist in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according  to the Agatston-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: Chest radiograph 1/30/2018.     FINDINGS:    CALCIUM SCORE:  Left main coronary artery: 0  Left anterior descending coronary artery: 0  Circumflex coronary artery: 0  Right coronary artery: 0    Agatston score: 0  The estimated probability of a non-zero calcium score for a group of patients asymptomatic for  coronary artery disease with the same age, race/ethnicity and sex is 81%.    OTHER FINDINGS:   Sub-3 mm pulmonary nodules, for example in the right upper lobe (series 4, image 17), left upper  lobe (4/15), and left lower lobe (4/60). Mild dependent atelectasis. Tiny gastroesophageal hiatal  hernia. A couple of small foci of sclerosis within bilateral ribs, probably bone islands.      GUIDELINES FOR FOLLOW-UP of newly detected solid nodules incidentally detected on CT in persons 35  years or older. (2017 revision)    LOW-RISK PATIENT (Minimal or absent history of smoking or of other known risk factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then consider CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm  Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm  No routine follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then consider CT at 18-24 months      HIGH-RISK PATIENT (History of smoking or of other known risk factors)  For single nodule, size:  <6mm  Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6-8mm CT at 6-12 months; then CT at 18-24 months, if no change  >8mm Consider Pulmonary Medicine consultation for management, or follow-up with CT at 3 months    For multiple nodules, size of largest nodule:  <6mm Optional CT at 12 months*; If unchanged, no further follow-up required  6mm or > CT at 3-6 months, then at 18-24 months    (Nodule size is the average of length and width.)    *Nodules <6mm do not require routine follow-up, but certain patients at high risk with suspicious  nodule morphology, upper lobe location, or both may warrant 12-month follow-up.      Guidelines do not apply to lung cancer screening, patients with immunosuppression, or patients with  a known primary cancer.          IMPRESSION:  1. Negative for coronary artery calcium. The observed coronary calcium score is 0.  2. Bilateral sub-3 mm pulmonary micronodules, which may not warrant follow-up in a low risk patient.  Management considerations are provided at the end of the report.

CT_report: Addendum Begins      DATE:   September 24, 2013       PROCEDURE: CORONARY CT ANGIOGRAM.       HISTORY:  A 60-year-old male with bicuspid aortic stenosis and    preoperative evaluation.       TECHNIQUE:  Dynamic volume Computed Tomography (Toshiba Aquilion One)    with prospectively electrocardiogram-triggerred acquisition through    the heart after intravenous injection of 70 mL Omnipaque 350 contrast    agent. The patient was premedicated with oral metoprolol tartrate and    sublingual nitroglycerin spray per protocol. One-heartbeat imaging    and reconstruction were performed at the best phase of the R-R    interval (70-80%).       CORONARY ARTERY CALCIUM SCORE:  The total Agatston score is 44.77.    This score is consistent with mild plaque burden and likely mild    coronary stenosis.        AORTIC VALVE CALCIUM SCORE:  The total Agatston score is 1497.       CORONARY ARTERY FINDINGS:   1. LEFT MAIN:  The left anterior descending and left circumflex    coronary arteries have separate ostia adjacent to each other in the    left sinus of Valsalva. No calcification and stenosis at the origins    of the left anterior descending and left circumflex coronary arteries.   2. LEFT ANTERIOR DESCENDING:  The left anterior descending coronary    artery is a type-3 vessel that reaches the left ventricular apex. It    gives rise to small diagonal branches. There is a small calcified    plaque in the proximal segment causing mild stenosis (15%). The    remaining left anterior descending coronary system is free of plaque    and widely patent.   3. LEFT CIRCUMFLEX:  The left circumflex coronary artery is a large    dominant vessel that gives rise to two small first and second obtuse    marginal branches and a large third obtuse marginal branch before    wrapping around the AV groove and subsequently giving rise to small    posterolateral branches and a large posterior descending artery. The left circumflex coronary system is free of plaque and widely patent.   4. RIGHT CORONARY ARTERY:  The right coronary artery is a nondominant    small vessel with normal origin in the right sinus of Valsalva. It is    patent and free of significant plaque.       NONCORONARY CARDIOVASCULAR FINDINGS:  The sinus of Valsalva is    measured at 31.6 mm in diameter. The proximal ascending aorta is    measured at 26.9 mm in diameter. The thoracic descending aorta is    measured at 23.3 mm in diameter. No significant atherosclerosis in    the thoracic aorta within the field of view. The aortic valve is    bicuspid with anterior-posterior orientation. The right coronary    artery and left coronary artery originate from the anterior cusp.    Normally connected right and left pulmonary veins. No evidence of    intracardiac shunt. Maximum left ventricular wall thickness is 12 mm.    No evidence of thrombus in the left atrial appendage. No pericardial    effusion. Normally connected superior vena cava and inferior vena    cava.        IMPRESSION:    1. Coronary calcium score of 44.77 consistent with mild plaque burden.   2. Left dominant coronary system.   3. Nondominant right coronary artery with no significant plaque and    stenosis.    4. Mild nonobstructive calcified plaque (15%) in the proximal segment    of the left anterior descending coronary artery. The remaining left    anterior descending coronary system is widely patent and free of    plaque.    5. Dominant left circumflex coronary artery with no significant    plaque or stenosis.    6. Bicuspid aortic valve with anterior-posterior orientation and    total calcium score of 1497.   7. No evidence of aortic dilatation within the field of view.   8. No significant aortic atherosclerosis within the field of view.       This is Dr. Le's dictation in the absence of Dr. Rozich. A negative scan makes the presence of atherosclerotic plaque or significant luminal obstructive disease very unlikely. Coronary calcium score = 0%.       Indeterminate 6 mm solid nodule within the peripheral left lower lobe lateral basal segment (series 2 image 77). CT_report: EXAM:  CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH IV CONTRAST    ECG-gated CT angiogram of the chest and heart, including independent workstation  3D reformations, performed per the TAVR procedure planning protocol.    COMPARISON: PA and lateral chest radiograph 04/06/2021    CARDIAC FINDINGS:      AORTIC VALVE:   Morphology:  Well-seated bioprosthetic aortic valve (23 mm St. Jude Trifecta).  Leaflet thickness:  Moderately increased prosthetic valve cusp thickness.  Leaflet mobility: Moderate restriction of prosthetic valve leaflet motion.  Leaflet calcification:  Severe calcification of the prosthetic valve cusps.   Calcium score: Not applicable.  LVOT Calcification: Mild discrete calcifications in the left ventricular outflow  tract below the neosurgical annulus along the aorto mitral curtain. Mixed  density surgical material is noted just below the prosthetic valve ring  consistent with a combination of felt material, dystrophic calcification, and  pannus.  Other findings: None    AORTIC VALVE/ANNULUS MEASUREMENTS  Surgical Neo-Aortic Valve Annulus (cardiac phase 75% R-R interval):  *  Diameter = 19.9 x 19.0 mm  *  Area = 3.01 sq cm  *  Average diameter = 19.6 mm  *  Perimeter = 61.9 mm    Distance from Aortic Valve Annulus to:  *  Left main coronary artery origin = 4.9 mm  *  Right coronary artery origin = 7.4 mm  *  Sinotubular junction = 14.2 mm  *  Brachiocephalic artery origin = 82.6 mm    Virtual Valve to Coronary Distance (20mm S3 valve prosthesis)  *  Left main coronary artery ostium = 8.8 mm  *  Right coronary artery ostium = 6.9 mm    Virtual Valve to Coronary Distance (23mm S3 valve prosthesis)  *  Left main coronary artery ostium = 8.1 mm  *  Right coronary artery ostium = 5.1 mm    Left Ventricular Outflow Tract 4 mm below the surgical prosthesis ring /  measured neo-aortic annulus (cardiac phase 75% R-R interval); this is through  the region of the pannus/felt material below the valve.  *  Diameter = 19.9 x 17.6 mm *  Area = 2.95 sq cm  *  Average diameter = 19.4 mm  *  Perimeter = 61.7 mm    Aortic Annulus Orthogonal Plane Angles:  *  Optimized Aortic Valve Plane N, R, L = 11 LAO; 9 CRA  *  Craniocaudal tilt at 0 degrees LAO = 2 CRA  *  Craniocaudal tilt at 10 degrees LAO = 8 CRA  *  Craniocaudal tilt at 10 degrees RAO = 5 CAU  *  R, L Cusp Overlap View = 7 RAO ; 3 CAU    CORONARY ARTERIES:   Coronary artery calcium score = 6079.8.   Overall image quality for coronary evaluation: Non-Diagnostic, Coronary Arteries  Partially Evaluable  Extensive three-vessel coronary artery calcifications. Extensive calcific plaque  limits assessment for coronary stenosis. Coronary artery anatomy is right  dominant.    OTHER CARDIAC FINDINGS:   The overall heart size is mildly enlarged, with prominent enlargement of the  left atrium and left ventricle. The right atrium and right ventricle are within  normal limits of size.  Rightward systolic excursion of the interventricular  septum is appreciated consistent with history of prior cardiac surgery.  Concentric left ventricular hypertrophy without other regional wall motion  abnormalities; left ventricular systolic function is qualitatively preserved.  Qualitatively preserved right ventricular systolic function. Mild mitral annular  calcification laterally. The mitral leaflets are moderately thickened.    Normal left ventricular apex. Physiologic pericardial fluid. No chamber filling  defects concerning for thrombus.    VASCULAR FINDINGS:  Thoracic Aorta: Surgical changes from prior cannulation of the ascending aorta  with felt material. No significant calcifications of the ascending aorta.  No  porcelain aorta.  The aortic arch is left-sided with 3 branches conventional  branching anatomy. Mild mixed density plaque is seen in the arch and descending  thoracic aorta with scattered foci of plaque ulceration. The thoracic aorta is  nondilated. The great vessel origins are minimally stenosed.  * Sinotubular Junction Diameter = 25.9 mm    The main, left, and right pulmonary arteries are enlarged suggesting elevated  pulmonary arterial pressures.    ADDITIONAL FINDINGS:    A peripherally calcified somewhat bilobed 34 x18 x 16 mm right thyroid nodule is  seen (series 5 image 115).    Small layering bilateral pleural effusions with segmental dependent right and  subsegmental dependent left atelectasis.    Well-healed midline osteotomy with intact sternal manubrial wires. Moderate  multilevel thoracic spine degenerative disc disease with flowing osteophytes in  the mid to lower thoracic spine. Partially visualized left glenohumeral  degenerative joint disease.    IMPRESSION:  1. Bioprosthetic aortic valve with moderate leaflet thickening and severe  prosthetic leaflet calcification. Dystrophic calcification and pannus is noted  along the surgical aortic annulus, immediately inferior to the valve ring. The  LVOT dimensions were obtained along the inner margin of this circumferential  material. Both 20 mm and 23 mm S3 prostheses were modeled for implantation.  Please see TAVR procedure planning measurements in the Findings section.    2. Three-vessel calcific coronary artery disease. Assessment for coronary  stenosis was limited due to extensive coronary calcific atherosclerosis.  Coronary calcium score = 6079.8.  3. Small bilateral pleural effusions with associated dependent lower lobe  atelectasis.  4. 34 x 18 x 16 mm somewhat bilobed right thyroid nodule with peripheral  calcifications. Based on size criteria a thyroid sonogram is suggested for  further characterization.

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC ANGIOGRAM WITH CORONARY ARTERIES WITH IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: Chest pain, evaluate for coronary disease, patient has  normal EKG.    TECHNIQUE: CT Coronary Angiography utilizing intravenous contrast and  prospective ECG-gating according to prospective coronary protocol. Pre-contrast  coronary calcium scoring was performed with prospective ECG-gating.     3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and  rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on a  workstation with 3D capabilities.    COMPARISON: Chest CT performed 7/4/2018 is available for comparison.    CORONARY FINDINGS: The patient has normal coronary anatomy. Coronary circulation  is Right dominant.    Calcium Score: Left main = zero; Left anterior descending = zero; Circumflex =  zero; Right =zero  Total score: zero    Left main coronary artery: Appears normal in size, free of any significant  atherosclerotic disease or narrowing.    Left anterior descending coronary artery system: Normal with normal diagonal  branches, no disease; no stenosis.    Left circumflex coronary artery: Normal with normal obtuse marginal branches, no  disease; no stenosis. Of note, the proximal portion of a large OM1, see series  10 image 78, is degraded by cardiac motion artifact although there are no  definite calcifications in this region    Right coronary artery: Normal with normal posterior descending branch, no  disease; no stenosis.    OTHER FINDINGS: No pericardial effusion. Heart appears normal in size. Aortic  valve is normal in appearance, tricuspid.    Somewhat expiratory technique with some motion artifact. Some bronchial wall  thickening suggests underlying asthma or bronchitis. Atelectasis, mild air  trapping, lungs otherwise clear. No adenopathy within visualized portions of the  chest and abdomen.     Visualized portions of the upper abdomen are unremarkable. The left fifth and  sixth ribs are partially fused, series 10 image 95, not sure if this finding  could be related to any left-sided chest pain?        IMPRESSION:    Total calcium score: 0 A zero coronary calcium score in an asymptomatic patient  is associated with a high negative predictive value for hard cardiac events  (myocardial infarction and cardiac related death), exceeding 95% and probably  approaching or exceeding 99%.    Coronary CT angiography shows some image degradation related to some gating  artifact, a small portion of the proximal OM1 coronary artery is degraded by  motion artifact. No definite coronary disease, no obvious areas of stenosis.     CADS-RAD category (based on most severe lesion): 0N (no stenosis, some artifact  degrades image quality but only mildly)    Findings in the lungs suggestive of some underlying asthma or bronchitis.    Partial fusion of left fifth and sixth ribs, perhaps somehow related to any  potential left-sided chest wall pain?      CAD-RADS CATEGORIES: (based on most severe single lesion)  0: 0%, No stenosis  1: 1-24%, Minimal stenosis  2: 25-49%, Mild stenosis  3: 50-69%, Moderate stenosis  4: 70-99%, Severe stenosis  5: 100%, Occluded    Modifiers:  N: Non-diagnostic segment(s)  S: Stent  G: Graft  V: Vulnerable plaque

CT_report: Indications: Nonrheumatic aortic (valve) stenosis;TAVR protocol   ORIGINAL REPORT - 11-Jul-2017 16:12:00   CT Angio Coronary   IMPRESSION:   1. Postprocedural changes of TVR with perivalvular leak due to lack of TAVR opposition inferior to the left sinus near the junction of the left and right commisures due to a 5 mm gap. Measurements as detailed below.   2. Resolution of previously described acute right-sided pulmonary emboli. Given the rapid interval disappearance in the lack of lower extremity deep venous thrombosis, it is possible that the areas of low-attenuation within the pulmonary arterial branches seen on the prior examination reflected prominent bronchial inflow artifact given that the aorta was unopacified at the time of that examination and the patient has multiple enlarged bronchial arteries related to the patient's underlying chronic parenchymal lung disease.   3. Persistent changes of bronchiectasis and bronchiolitis without consolidative pneumonia.      Coronary calcium score: 68 percentile.      Incidental findings      CLINICAL HISTORY: History of TAVR January 2016 with perivalvular leak. Plan for re-intervention.      TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 20%, 42% and 84% of the R-R interval.  The source 0.625 axial images were transferred to a 3-D workstation for multiplanar and 3-D reformatting. Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      COMPARE: CT Coronary 12/18/2015, CT chest 7/7/2017, 5/16/2017, 6/5/2016      Mediastinum: Borderline pretracheal nodal enlargement, largest measuring 11 mm short axis (series 12, image 147), similar to previous study. Multivessel coronary arterial calcium.  No significant pericardial abnormality. TAVR in place. Calcifications related to native bicuspid aortic valve. Multiple prominent bronchial arteries are again noted.      Pleura:] Small right pleural effusion, stable from CT chest 7/7/2017      Abdomen: No significant upper abdominal findings.      Lungs: The acute pulmonary emboli described on CT 7/7/2017 are no longer seen. Ssevere multifocal left bronchiectasis with several areas of tree-in-bud nodularity in the right upper lobe suggestive of bronchial impaction. Severe central airway thickening. Right apical bullous changes again noted.      Chest wall: No significant axillary lymph node enlargement.  No osseous lesions.      Aortic Measurements      Valve calcification: Heavy, particularly along the posterior leaflet extending into the interlobular fibrosa      Measurements in systole 20% R-R interval:   Aortic root measurement sinuses of Valsalva: 38.8 mm x 36.1 mm by 36.5 mm, mean = 37.1 mm. Area equals 11.0 centimeters squared.   The existing TAVR at the level of the native annulus measures 24.7 mm x 24.4 mm with an area of 4.72 cm squared.   The distance from the distal struts of the TAVR to the aortic annulus is approximately 1cm.   The TAVR is not opposed to the aorta wall beneath the left sinus which is the likely site of the perivalvular leak. The crescentic gap measures up to 5 mm. Distance from left main coronary artery to the basal ring: 17.5 mm.   Right sinus height (base of sinus to near ST junction, mm): 18.4  mm   Left sinus height (base of sinus to near ST junction, mm): 19.7 mm.   Aortic angulation: 50 degrees   Aortic diameter measurement at 3 cm cranial to annulus: 37.6 mm x 38.5 mm Aortic diameter measurement at 4 cm cranial to annulus: 38.5  mm x 41.1 mm      Incidental note of independent origins of the LAD and LCx directly from the aorta at the same level. CT_report: Indications: ABNORMAL STRESS TEST 123092 NITIN MAHAJAN 915 532 6767   ORIGINAL REPORT - 25-Jun-2015 13:54:00   CT Angio Coronary   IMPRESSION:   1. No obstructive coronary disease is seen. There is an abrupt change of caliber of the left anterior descending coronary artery at the mid to distal junction just proximal to the region of myocardial bridging with a diagonal coronary branch coursing into the distal left anterior descending coronary territory as well as reemergence of the distal left anterior descending beyond the level of bridging with opacification of these vessels. This is likely a congenital variant. Correlation for site of stress examination abnormality is recommended.      HISTORY: Abnormal stress examination.      Technique:   HEART AND CORONARY ARTERIES ANGIO CT TECHNIQUE: ECG gated 3D short, vertical long, and horizontal long axis maximum intensity projections; 3D volume renderings; and curved reformats performed to better evaluate coronary arteries. Iodinated contrast media administered intravenously; see PowerChart for the amounts and type of iodinated contrast media administered and wasted.      COMPARISON: Abdomen pelvis CT 3/31/2015      FINDINGS:      Coronary calcium score is 0.      The left and right coronary artery arises from the appropriate coronary sinuses and have normal courses. The patient is right heart dominant with the posterior descending coronary artery and posterior lateral ventricular branch arising from the right coronary artery.      There is no evidence of disease of the left main coronary artery. The left anterior descending coronary artery is without plaque or focal stenosis. The mid to distal left anterior descending coronary artery becomes diminutive in size just proximal to a portion of short myocardial bridging. However the distal left anterior descending artery remains opacified. 2 diagonal coronary arteries are seen with the second diagonal coursing along the distal left anterior descending coronary territory.      Circumflex coronary artery is without stenosis or disease. There is an early proximal obtuse marginal branch which is without stenosis.      Heart is normal in size and there is a tiny anterior inferior pericardial effusion. There is minimal left basilar atelectasis. Visualized portions of the lungs clear. Visualized portions of the upper abdomen demonstrate a stable low-attenuation peripherally calcified pseudocyst within the tail of the pancreas.         Electronically signed by:    Kristopher Cummings, M.D. 25-Jun-2015 13:54
