CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: None    TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification  scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial  reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation  in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: None    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       ADDITIONAL FINDINGS: 4 x 2 mm left lower lobe nodule, series 3 image 47, has a  benign appearance. Note is made of an anomalous left circumflex coronary artery  arising from a common ostium with the right coronary artery and taking a  retroaortic course, a benign variant. Otherwise, Visualized portions of the  lungs, mediastinum and upper abdomen are normal. No concerning osseous lesions  are seen.    IMPRESSION:  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 50% of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.    Incidental note is made of an anomalous retroaortic left circumflex coronary  artery arising from right coronary artery, a benign variation.

CT_report: Indications: Pure hypercholesterolemia;CAD   ORIGINAL REPORT - 07-Oct-2016 16:13:00   CT Angio Coronary      IMPRESSION: Normal appearing coronary arteries, no significant coronary artery disease..      Coronary calcium score: 0]      Mild bronchitis/bronchiolitis most noticeable in the lingula, favor infectious/inflammatory etiology. Patient could be recovered from bronchopneumonia or viral infection. Nontuberculous mycobacterial infection would be a secondary consideration, less likely consideration at this point.         CLINICAL HISTORY: Hypercholesterolemia, clinical concern for coronary artery disease.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 70% of the R-R interval.  The source 0.625 axial images were transferred to a 3-D workstation for multiplanar and 3-D reformatting. Short and long axis views and rotating oblique reformatted views were also performed of the coronary arteries. Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      Premedication with Metoprolol and Nitroglycerine performed as per Departmental protocol.         COMPARE: Calcium scoring CT performed 10/1/2013 is available for comparison.         VASCULAR FINDINGS: Patient has normal coronary anatomy with a right dominant coronary circulation..      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 0. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 0 , left circumflex 0, and right coronary artery 0.      Left main coronary artery: The left main coronary artery is a normal-sized vessel, free of atherosclerotic disease, no stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: The left anterior descending coronary artery is a normal-sized vessel. The vessel and its major branches are free of any significant atherosclerotic disease. No CT evidence of stenosis.      Right coronary artery: The right coronary artery is a large artery. There is some mild irregularity within the vertical segment of the right coronary artery which is related to some mild cardiac motion artifact. The artery and its major branches appear free of any significant atherosclerotic disease, no CT evidence of stenosis.      Left circumflex coronary artery: The left circumflex is a normal sized artery. The artery and its major branches appear free of any significant atherosclerotic disease, no CT evidence of stenosis. The left circumflex artery ends as a second obtuse marginal branch which demonstrates some mild myocardial bridging.      Ramus intermedius: There is a large ramus intermedius branch containing a long segment of myocardial bridging. No atherosclerotic disease, no CT evidence of stenosis.      Heart is normal in size. There could be some mild circumferential left ventricular hypertrophy, difficult to say for certain. No significant pericardial effusion. Aortic valve is tricuspid but appears somewhat thickened, could represent some developing aortic valve degeneration, no significant valvular calcification seen. Main pulmonary artery is 31 mm and, upper limits of normal in size. No large central or lobar filling defects are seen to suggest pulmonary emboli.      NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Some very mild tree-in-bud nodularity and bronchial mucous plugging noted most prominent in the lingula, to a lesser degree within the medial aspect of the right middle lobe and in the lower lobes there is also some atelectasis. Findings are most consistent with some mild bronchitis/bronchiolitis perhaps infectious in origin. Some mildly prominent mediastinal lymph nodes are likely reactive. Limited evaluation of the upper abdomen is unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen.         Electronically signed by:    C. E. Jokerst M.D. 07-Oct-2016 16:13

CT_report: Indications: Angina pectoris with documented spasm;PRIZMETHAL ANGINA/ CHANGE IN PATERN/ RULE OUT OBSTRUCTIVE CAD/ OBTAIN CALCIUM SCORE   ORIGINAL REPORT - 30-Jun-2017 15:10:00   CT Angio Coronary         IMPRESSION: Mild three-vessel coronary artery atherosclerotic calcifications as described below.      Some mild irregularity of the mid to distal LAD and a focal mild point of narrowing in the vertical segment of the right coronary artery do not appear to be associated with any atherosclerotic disease. While these findings could be related to mild noncalcified atherosclerotic disease, I suspect they all are manifestations of mild coronary vasospasm especially given the patient's history of Prinzmetal's angina.      Coronary calcium score: 200.  This is a moderate calcium score generally associated with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related death) of up to 4.3 times patients with 0 calcium scores. MESA percentile 94%.         CLINICAL HISTORY: Angina, worsening over the past few weeks. Patient has a history of Prinzmetal's angina. Patient also has left bundle branch block.         TECHNIQUE: Calcium scoring was performed without intravenous contrast using prospective ECG triggering and reconstruction of contiguous axial images through the heart at 70% of the R-R interval.  Images were post-processed on an independent 3-D workstation in order to calculate the patient's calcium score.      Intravenous contrast was administered and a prospectively R-wave triggered step-and-shoot cardiac acquisition was performed with reconstruction of images at 70% of the R-R interval.    Iodinated contrast administered intravenously. Please see Powerchart for amount and type of iodinated contrast administered and wasted due to the use of single dose vials.      3-D reconstructions including volume rendering and short and long axis and rotating oblique reformatted views of the coronary arteries were performed on an independent 3-D workstation.      Premedication with Metoprolol performed as per Departmental protocol. Nitroglycerin was held due to the fact the patient is on long-acting nitroglycerin patch. Patient has a history of minor hives with intravenous contrast in the past, tolerated intravenous contrast well today, no complications.            COMPARE: Chest radiograph 3/24/2017; catheter angiography 4/13/2011.         VASCULAR FINDINGS: The patient has right dominant coronary circulation..      Coronary arteries:  Total calcium score equals 200. Coronary artery calcification scores are as follows: left main 0, left anterior descending artery 113 , left circumflex 13, and right coronary artery 74.      Left main coronary artery: Normal size vessel, no atherosclerotic disease, no stenosis.      Left anterior descending coronary artery: Normal size vessel. There is mild calcified eccentric atherosclerotic plaque within the proximal and mid LAD. Focal plaques within the proximal and mid LAD causing mild, less than 50% and probably less than 30%, loss of diameter. A small plaque at the origin of a large first diagonal coronary artery branch also causes mild, less than 30% loss of diameter. Mild irregularity noted in portions of the mid to distal LAD do not appear to correspond to areas of noncalcified plaque, findings could be manifestations of vasospasm given the patient's history.      Right coronary artery: A large artery. Some mild eccentric calcified plaque in the proximal horizontal and vertical segments of the right coronary artery causes mild, less than 30% loss of luminal diameter. There is a focal area of mild stenosis within the vertical section of the right coronary artery with mild, less than 30% loss of diameter. Difficult to tell if finding is related to circumferential noncalcified plaque or vasospasm, favor the latter given the patient's history.      Left circumflex coronary artery: A normal-sized vessel. Some very mild eccentric calcified plaque in the proximal left circumflex does not appear to cause any narrowing of the vessel lumen. First branch of the left circumflex is an anatomic variant small obtuse marginal branch which also gives rise to a septal perforator branch. The left circumflex also gives off an SA nodal branch. There is a large second obtuse marginal branch which is free of any significant stenosis or atherosclerotic disease.      The heart is normal in size. No pericardial effusion. Thoracic aorta is normal in course and caliber, no acute aortic pathology. Central pulmonary arteries are normal in appearance, no large central pulmonary emboli are seen.      NON-VASCULAR FINDINGS: Very mild thickening of the airways which could be a reflection of some chronic bronchitis. Patient has a smoking history, otherwise could perhaps be related to infectious bronchitis or asthma. The lungs are otherwise clear. No pleural effusion, no pneumothorax. No thoracic lymphadenopathy. Visualized portions of the upper abdomen are unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen. CT_report: Indications: Tobacco Use Pers Hx - Personal History;Cancer screening   ORIGINAL REPORT - 14-Sep-2015 07:35:00   CT Lung Cancer Screen Low Dose   IMPRESSION:      1. Category 1 negative screening exam. Return to annual screening if risk factors persists.      CATEGORY 1:  NEGATIVE   CATEGORY DESCRIPTOR:  No nodules and definitely benign nodules.   FINDINGS:  No lung nodules or nodule(s) with specific calcifications: complete, central, popcorn, concentric rings and fat containing nodules. MANAGEMENT:  Continue annual screening with LDCT in12 months.      HISTORY: Lung cancer screening      EXAM: Low dose lung cancer screening CT scan of the Chest without contrast. Coronal and sagittal maximum intensity projections performed to better evaluate for pulmonary nodules; the charge for these is included in the bundled price.      COMPARISON: Coronary calcium score CT 12/26/2006      FINDINGS: 4 mm nodule in the right middle lobe at image 350 is noncalcified but does not appear significantly changed in comparison to the 2006 coronary calcium scoring exam. There is a calcified granuloma in the right middle lobe more superiorly. Minimal peripheral reticulation in the upper lobes is noted using the possibility of a minimal component of nonspecific fibrosis. There is no honeycombing. There is some minimal dependent atelectasis and there is mild bronchial wall thickening seen in the upper greater than lower lobes with some minimal associated respiratory bronchiolitis as evidenced by faint centrilobular nodules of mild severity in the upper lobes. There is no focal consolidation, pleural effusion or mass lesion.      There is no supraclavicular, axillary, mediastinal or hilar lymphadenopathy. A few subcentimeter nonpathologically enlarged mediastinal nodes are seen. Moderate calcification of the thoracic aorta is noted with severe coronary calcification. No pericardial effusion.      Visualized portions of the upper abdomen normal in appearance. No osseous lesion is seen.         Electronically signed by:    Kristopher Cummings, M.D. 14-Sep-2015 07:35

CT_report: EXAM: CT CARDIAC SCORING WITHOUT IV CONTRAST    ADDITIONAL HISTORY: Screening    TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification  scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial  reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation  in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the  Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold.    COMPARISON: 5/27/2004cardiac scoring CT    FINDINGS:      Score:  Left main coronary artery: zero    Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero    Circumflex coronary artery: zero    Right coronary artery: zero      Total score: zero       INCIDENTAL FINDINGS:   LUNGS:  No suspicious nodules, masses, consolidation, or pneumothorax.  Visualized central airways clear.    MEDIASTINUM:  Heart size normal with no pericardial effusion.  The ascending thoracic aorta at the level of the pulmonic valve is dilated up to  4.3 cm, previously 4.1 cm on 5/27/2004.    PLEURA:  No pleural abnormality. No pleural effusion.    No hilar, or mediastinal lymphadenopathy in the visualized chest.    No suspicious osseous lesion.    The visualized intraabdominal organs are unremarkable.     IMPRESSION:  1.  Coronary artery calcium score of zero. 0-36 percent of patients in an age,  gender and ethnicity matched cohort have a zero calcium score. A zero coronary  calcium score in an asymptomatic patient is associated with a high negative  predictive value for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac  related death), exceeding 95% and probably approaching or exceeding 99%.  2.  Dilation of the ascending thoracic aorta to 4.3 cm.

TECHNIQUE:  CT of the heart was done according to coronary artery calcification_x000D_
scoring protocol with prospective ECG gating and diastolic-phase axial_x000D_
reconstructions. Postprocessing was performed on an independent 3D workstation_x000D_
in order to calculate the patient's calcium score according to the_x000D_
Agatson-Janowitz scale with a 130 HU threshold._x000D_
_x000D_

_x000D_
_x000D_

Left main coronary artery: 4  _x000D_
Left anterior descending coronary artery: zero  _x000D_
Circumflex coronary artery: zero  _x000D_
Right coronary artery: zero  _x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
Total score: 4   _x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
INCIDENTAL FINDINGS: There are a few small nodules along the minor fissure for_x000D_
example, 4 mm nodule series 3 image 15, triangular 5 x 3 mm nodule series 3_x000D_
image 18 consistent with benign nodules. Dependent atelectasis, visualized lungs_x000D_
otherwise clear. Mild fusiform aneurysmal dilatation of the ascending aorta up_x000D_
to 43 mm. No significant adenopathy within visualized portions of the lower_x000D_
chest and upper abdomen, no pericardial effusion, Limited evaluation of the_x000D_
upper abdomen unremarkable. No lytic or blastic osseous lesions are seen._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
IMPRESSION: Coronary artery calcium score of 4. 47th percentile compared to age_x000D_
and gender matched controls. This is a low calcium score generally associated_x000D_
with a risk for hard cardiac events (myocardial infarction and cardiac-related_x000D_
death) of up to 1.9 times patients with 0 calcium scores._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
No significant incidental findings._x000D_
